%%%
metricsum — metric-aware Einstein summation showcase.

FlatPPL's `metricsum(metric, output_axes, expr)` (with the
`metric: result[output_indices] := expr` shorthand from spec section
05) extends `aggregate(sum, ...)` with explicit upper / lower index
tracking. Each `.name^` is contravariant (upper); each `.name_` is
covariant (lower). Per spec section 04 sec:metricsum:

- The `metric` argument stores `g^{ij}` (contravariant). `inv(metric)`
  is `g_{ij}` (covariant). Arrays carry no tensor metadata outside
  metricsum — they hold the all-upper canonical components.
- A lower-variance axis access `v[.i_]` evaluates to
  `v_i = g_{i,alpha} v^alpha`.
- The output is stored in all-upper canonical layout, so a `.i_` output
  is automatically raised: stored `T^i = g^{i,alpha} T_alpha`.

The shorthand `g: result[...] := expr` desugars (in the parser) to
`result = metricsum(g, [...], expr)`. The lift pass then rewrites
every metricsum() call to a sum-`aggregate(...)` with inv(metric)
factors (one per lower-variance body access) + metric factors (one
per lower-variance output axis), per the spec lowering rule.

Numerical reference: this fixture uses a 2D Minkowski-signature
metric `g^{ij} = diag(+1, -1)` (self-inverse: `inv(g) == g`).
Lower-indexing a vector flips the sign of the spatial component.
%%%
flatppl_compat = "0.1"

# 2D Minkowski metric: g^{ij} = diag(+1, -1). Self-inverse under
# inversion. Stored as a 2x2 array of scalars.
g = [[1.0, 0.0], [0.0, -1.0]]

# Vectors stored as all-upper components.
# p^i = (E=3, px=2), q^i = (1, 4).
p = [3.0, 2.0]
q = [1.0, 4.0]

# 2x2 identity matrix, stored upper-upper. Three copies for the
# Lorentz-composition test below.
M_id = [[1.0, 0.0], [0.0, 1.0]]
L1   = [[1.0, 0.0], [0.0, 1.0]]
L2   = [[1.0, 0.0], [0.0, 1.0]]
L3   = [[1.0, 0.0], [0.0, 1.0]]

%%%
Lorentz-invariant norm: `p . p = p^i p_i = (p^0)^2 - (p^1)^2 = 9 - 4 = 5`.
The body `p[.i^] * p[.i_]` mixes upper and lower access of the same
vector; the empty output `[]` produces a scalar.
%%%
g: norm_pp[] := p[.i^] * p[.i_]

%%%
Cross inner product: `p^i q_i = p^0 q_0 + p^1 q_1`. With Minkowski
metric, `q_0 = g_{0,alpha} q^alpha = +q^0`,
`q_1 = g_{1,alpha} q^alpha = -q^1`. So result = 3*1 + 2*(-4) = -5.
Same value as `p_i q^i` because the metric is symmetric (a spec
requirement).
%%%
g: inner_pq[] := p[.i^] * q[.i_]

%%%
Mixed-variance matvec with the identity matrix. M_id is stored
upper-upper as the identity; its mixed-variance form is
    M_id^i_j = M_id^{i,alpha} g_{alpha,j} = g_{i,j}.
So `M_id[.i^, .j_] * q[.j^]` evaluates to `g_{i,j} q^j = q_i` —
i.e. q with its spatial component sign-flipped, raised back to
all-upper storage. For q = [1, 4] under Minkowski: result = [1, -4].
%%%
g: lower_q[.i^] := M_id[.i^, .j_] * q[.j^]

%%%
Outer product via mixed variance: lowering then raising the SAME
index is the identity transformation, so this evaluates to the
plain outer product p^i q^j regardless of the metric (under any
non-singular symmetric metric, per spec). The body's `q[.j_]` (lower
access) pairs with the OUTPUT axis `.j_` (lower variance) — so the
metric raise of the output exactly cancels the metric lower of the
access (`g_{j,alpha} g^{alpha,sigma} = delta^sigma_j`).
For p = [3, 2], q = [1, 4]:
    p outer q = [[3*1, 3*4], [2*1, 2*4]] = [[3, 12], [2, 8]]
A strong invariance test — the stored result is identical to plain
outer product despite the metric appearing twice in the lowered IR.
%%%
g: outer_pq[.i^, .j_] := p[.i^] * q[.j_]

%%%
Spec example: composition of three Lorentz transformations as
(1,1)-tensors. With all three factors set to upper-upper identity,
each factor evaluates to `L^i_j = g_{i,j}` in mixed-variance form.
The metric is Minkowski-self-inverse so g_{i,a} g^{a,j} = delta^j_i,
which makes the overall mixed-variance composition collapse to
delta^i_k. Raised back to all-upper storage via `.k_ -> .k_up`, the
stored result is identity. Numerically:
    L_compose = [[1, 0], [0, 1]] for L1 = L2 = L3 = identity.
%%%
g: L_compose[.i^, .k_] := L1[.i^, .j_] * L2[.j^, .m_] * L3[.m^, .k_]

%%%
Sanity: under the identity metric, metricsum collapses to plain
`aggregate(sum, ...)` (spec sec:metricsum "Equivalence under
identity metric"). The lift still emits inv(metric) and metric
factors, but they reduce to identity contractions at runtime, so
the numerical result matches the corresponding plain matmul.

For A_mat = [[1,2],[3,4]], B_mat = [[5,6],[7,8]]:
    A @ B = [[19, 22], [43, 50]]
%%%
eye2 = [[1.0, 0.0], [0.0, 1.0]]
A_mat = [[1.0, 2.0], [3.0, 4.0]]
B_mat = [[5.0, 6.0], [7.0, 8.0]]
eye2: AB_eye[.i^, .k^] := A_mat[.i^, .j_] * B_mat[.j^, .k^]
